# Universal Coding Standards

These standards apply to ALL coding agents (Backend, Frontend, Testing, DevOps) across ALL phases.

## Immutability (Critical)

ALWAYS create new objects. NEVER mutate existing ones:

```
WRONG:  modify(original, field, value)  → changes original in-place
CORRECT: update(original, field, value) → returns new copy with change
```

Immutable data prevents hidden side effects, makes debugging easier, and enables safe concurrency.

## File Organization

MANY SMALL FILES > FEW LARGE FILES:
- High cohesion, low coupling
- 200–400 lines typical, 800 max
- Extract utilities from large modules
- Organize by feature/domain, not by type

## Error Handling

ALWAYS handle errors comprehensively:
- Handle errors explicitly at every level
- Provide user-friendly messages in UI-facing code
- Log detailed context on the server side
- Never silently swallow errors
- Use typed/structured error objects over generic strings

## Input Validation

ALWAYS validate at system boundaries:
- Validate all user input before processing
- Use schema-based validation where available (Zod, Pydantic, Joi)
- Fail fast with clear error messages
- Never trust external data (API responses, user input, file content)

## Code Quality Checklist

Before marking any coding work complete:
- [ ] Code is readable and well-named
- [ ] Functions are small (<50 lines)
- [ ] Files are focused (<800 lines)
- [ ] No deep nesting (>4 levels)
- [ ] Proper error handling at every level
- [ ] No hardcoded values (use constants or config)
- [ ] No mutation (immutable patterns used)
- [ ] No dead code or unused imports

## Naming Conventions

- Functions: verb + noun (`getUserById`, `validateInput`, `calculateTotal`)
- Booleans: prefix with `is`, `has`, `should`, `can` (`isActive`, `hasPermission`)
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE for true constants
- Files: match the primary export name

## Rules

- EVERY coding agent must follow these standards
- Violations found during code review are MEDIUM severity minimum
- The Testing Agent should verify these in code review checks
- The Learning Agent should log recurring violations as lessons
